post_text:
Steve wonders:

… If everyone on the Earth jumped in the air at the same
time, how much less would the Earth weigh?

… If I am in a falling elevator and I execute a jump up in
the air at the perfect time (just before impact), could I
save myself?

… You would think that no one could stand on anything
rotating over 900 mph (depending on your latitude), but
we all are doing that!

… Last year a gravitational wave from two black holes
merging hit the Earth. As Einstein postulated,
gravitational waves can bend the fabric of time. Did we
experience any time flux in that moment?

post_text:
IDEAS FOR STUDYING
 Create a study guide by topic. Formulate questions and problems
and write complete answers. Create your own quiz.
 Become a teacher. Say the information aloud in your own words
as if you are the instructor and teaching the concepts to a class.
 Derive examples that relate to your own experiences.
 Create concept maps or diagrams that explain the material.
 Develop symbols that represent concepts.
 For non-technical classes (e.g., English, History, etc.), figure out
the big ideas so you can explain, contrast, and re-evaluate them.
 For technical classes, work the problems and explain the steps
and why they work.
 Study in terms of question, evidence, and conclusion: What is the
question posed by the instructor/author? What is the evidence
that they present? What is the conclusion?

post_text:
By now, students should have a weekly routine for school and
homework. With due dates, test dates, homework, and classwork,
students have to remember a long list. One thing that helps is to have
an actual physical reminder, something you can see each day.

A calendar, poster board, sticky notes, charts, and graphs are all
excellent examples. You can see what is expected each day, what is
due in a few days, and when the exams are scheduled. You are
demonstrating a skill that many adults have a hard time with, time
management. It is not easy, and the older you get, the more things pile
up on your list.

post_text:
Students, have you noticed that teachers are covering a lot of material in a short amount of time? Does it seem like you have twice (or more) as much homework as you did in elementary school? The reason is quite simple. We need you to be able to take an Honors Algebra class at least by 8th grade, take an AP Government exam in the 9th grade (typically a Senior level class), pass Honors and AP courses while completing dual enrollment college courses, and perform at a very high level. Through a variety of methods, our teachers provide an accelerated program, utilize curriculum compacting, differentiate instruction, and provide a rigorous curriculum with demanding assessments.
You will be well prepared for college by the end of the 9th or 10th grade.

DEAR AIMS STUDENTS AND FAMILIES
Wow, another week goes by. The students and teachers have been remarkable in adapting to the online format. I am amazed at the teachers’ ability to use the tools and technology to teach. Their ability to adapt and change from what and how they were taught to teach and how their experience shaped their teaching to the current practice has been inspiring.
Of course, when things change again, everyone will have to adapt again. The school has plans and ideas, but we are at the mercy of the current Health Orders from the state. Thinking about all of the possible schedules and configurations of what school will be next can be exhausting. We will be ready, but we cannot predict what will be next.

post_text:
From Dr. Eckert
What do we do with the changes and losses in the new age? Gone for now are Intensive classes, House, lunchtime, fire drills, four-square games, archery, science expo, vending machines, forgotten water bottles, lost and found, rolling backpacks, student pick-up and drop-off, Mr. John’s weekly corny jokes, Mr. Watje’s basketball games, school dances, and on and on. Change and loss are different. Change may mean something ends, but it implies something begins. We are all experiencing this change at the same time, and the beginnings will depend upon how we can all work together to achieve our goals.

From Dr. Eckert
What do we do with the changes and losses in the new age? Gone for now are Intensive classes, House, lunchtime, fire drills, four-square games, archery, science expo, vending machines, forgotten water bottles, lost and found, rolling backpacks, student pick-up and drop-off, Mr. John’s weekly corny jokes, Mr. Watje’s basketball games, school dances, and on and on. Change and loss are different. Change may mean something ends, but it implies something begins. We are all experiencing this change at the same time, and the beginnings will depend upon how we can all work together to achieve our goals.

AIMS@UNM participates in NAACP ACT-SO
The NAACP’s Afro-Academic, Cultural, Technological and Scientific Olympics (ACT-SO) is a yearlong achievement program designed to recruit, stimulate, and encourage high academic and cultural achievement among African-American high school students.

ACT-SO includes 32 competitions in STEM, humanities, business, and performing, visual and culinary arts. Almost 300,000 young people have participated from the program since its inception.

For over forty years the mission of ACT-SO has been to prepare, recognize and reward youth of African descent who exemplify scholastic and artistic excellence.

post_text:
504 PLANS AND BEHAVIOR INTERVENTION PLANS
Some students may require a 504 Plan or Behavior Intervention Plan (BIP). Section 504 Plans are part of the Vocational and Rehabilitation Act that identifies accommodations for people who have a disability using the Americans with Disabilities Act definitions of a disabling condition. Accommodations are listed and monitored to provide the needed support the student requires.

A BIP is developed after the school conducts a Functional Behavioral Assessment for any student exhibiting behaviors that impede the student's success (or impedes the success of other students in the room as well). The BIP states the behavior(s) of concern, outlines interventions and accommodations, and identifies rewards and consequences.

The school will work with the family and student to develop a 504 Plan or a BIP. Both plans are designed to provide supports for the student with the goal of being a temporary or intermittent service, and developing the student's skills necessary to become successful.

post_text:
It was started by two brothers as a place to show their hobby began to grow by leaps & bounds. Soon they were joined by other 'Model Railroad Clubs' and other craftsmen. Some were electricians, model makers, carpenters, computer programmers. Their wives would stop by to see what they were doing and usually bring them a lunch.

One thing led to another. Three of the ladies had worked at a bakery, several visitors would ask if they had a snack bar. The idea was planted; some of the carpenters came and built a nice restaurant area for the bakery and a kitchen, too. If the fresh coffee smell didn't get you, then the bakery definitely would. Over 400,000 man-hours were spent making this dream come true.

This was about 5 years ago. One of the breweries came and furnished all the tables and chairs, serving counter etc. Their latest finished area is the airport. Planes look like they are flying and landing. GERMAN WONDERLAND IN HAMBURG - AMAZING!

post_text:
Great news from NM #1 school....

AIMS@UNM class of 2023 (Freshmen last year) outscored the global pass rate/mean scores on the A.P. United States Government and Politics Exam.

The global pass rate (score of 3 or above to earn college credit) was 57.5% and we are at 58% (New Mexico as a state came in at 30.9%).

Our mean score (2.9) also bested the global and New Mexico mean scores (G 2.84, NM 2.04). This is really great news for the following reasons:

- Our kids take this course and exam as freshmen - 9th grade, whereas the course is predominantly taught at the 12th grade level elsewhere.

- ALL of our kids take the exam, whereas it's mostly optional elsewhere (often the most confident/advised will sign up, pay for and take the exam).

- AIMS@UNM pays for all our students' exams.

- The kids truly stepped up in the face of strange and challenging circumstances.

- We had eight scores of a 5 (17% of our test takers and global is 16%). It may be the highest number of 5s scored on any of our AP exams over the years

Way to go Archers

post_text: Thank you for providing the well thought out options for the fall semester for our kids. We discussed the two options and feel that it would be best for our child to attend AIMS virtually this fall.
text: Thank you for providing the well thought out options for the fall semester for our kids. We discussed the two options and feel that it would be best for our child to attend AIMS virtually this fall.

post_text:
"First let me start by saying that my wife and I don’t envy you for the decisions you have to make and the monumental task that you and your team are up against. However, more importantly we are thankful for the open lines of communication and the admirable job that you and your team have been doing to support our daughter’s education. We continue to be thankful to be part of the AIMS community.

As you will note from the attachment, we’ve elected to have our daughter attend virtually for the 1st semester due to our concerns regarding recent trends. If possible and reasonable, we hope to have the opportunity to re-evaluate this decision at the end of the semester.

Fingers crossed and God willing our communities find the resolve to persevere, and the world’s scientists and doctors find the keys to defeating this pandemic!"

- AIMS Parent

After reading several parent quotes re: school opening, an AIMS parent wanted to share something with the AIMS@UNM family.

We encourage all parents to share their thoughts. Together we will remain the state's #1 school and a strong, resilient family.

“When our son came to AIMS he was excited to go to school for the first time. He found friendship and acceptance from both students and staff. He is ready to be back in school with his friends and teachers. We love and miss our AIMS family during these trying times. I know we will pull through this and the students will get back to learning at the #1 school in New Mexico. Thank you to all the teachers who are working so hard to plan for our children. Go Archers!”

post_text:
Galileo's Hypothesis.

Do you remember learning about Galileo, the father of physics, who was
born in Pisa, Italy, in 1564 and lived until 1642. He discovered the
Rings of Saturn, among other things? Galileo also discovered that any
object falling to earth, falls at the same rate.

He mentioned that a cannonball and a feather, if dropped from the same
height, will touch the ground at the same time provided there is no
air resistance. I always found this hard to believe.

Even Galileo had difficulty explaining it for quite a long time. Four
centuries later, with the current technology, it has been
experimentally demonstrated. Open the attachment, watch full screen to
view / listen to the verification experiment.

It's a great visual treat to watch

post_text:
AIMS@UNM began the Senior Class Mural tradition with the Class of 2013 and have continued to the present day as a chance for graduating Seniors to leave a colorful, imaginative, and celebratory mark on the campus walls.

Seniors collaborate throughout the year on the theme, design, and composition of the mural and usually have a full week to paint in May in between their AP exam and the Commencement ceremony.

The Class of 2020 has shown unusual resilience and patience to pull off this artwork in the midst of a pandemic, coming in independently to safely complete the mural.

Special recognition to Zoe Hughes '20 for volunteering to design and paint the background for the mural. Thank you, Zoe!

Here's a picture of talented Vy Vu finishing up the mural at our front desk.

Over the next days we'll be featuring the 2020 mural....

post_text:
Memorial Day was initially designed just for the Civil War
For more than 100 years, Memorial Day was reserved for honoring the lives of Civil War soldiers. The holiday didn’t expand to casualties of all American wars until after World War I. In 1971, it was declared a national holiday by an act of Congress. Find out why some states initially refused to celebrate Memorial Day.
text:
Memorial Day was initially designed just for the Civil War
For more than 100 years, Memorial Day was reserved for honoring the lives of Civil War soldiers. The holiday didn’t expand to casualties of all American wars until after World War I. In 1971, it was declared a national holiday by an act of Congress. Find out why some states initially refused to celebrate Memorial Day.

post_text:
Memorial Day was originally called Decoration Day.
The holiday was celebrated by “decorating” the graves of fallen soldiers with flowers, flags, and more, hence the name “Decoration Day.” Over time, it became known as Memorial Day.
text:
Memorial Day was originally called Decoration Day.
The holiday was celebrated by “decorating” the graves of fallen soldiers with flowers, flags, and more, hence the name “Decoration Day.” Over time, it became known as Memorial Day.

post_text:
Multiple cities claim to be the birthplace of Memorial Day.
According to the Library of Congress, President Lyndon Johnson declared Waterloo, New York, to be the "Birthplace of Memorial Day," referencing a celebration the town had in 1866. However, other places are known to have celebrated the holiday earlier, and exactly where the first celebration took place remains in dispute.
